---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Hooks: Make Things Happen Automatically, Without Reminders"
  description="Learn how to use Hooks to automatically run commands at specific points in Claude Code's lifecycle — desktop notifications, auto-formatting, and more."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container cc-hooks">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Connect Claude Code to Tools, Teach It New Tricks, and Automate Repetitive Work</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          We've already set up the basics for Claude Code — CLAUDE.md, memory management, context handling.
          The next stage isn't about stuffing more rules into the handbook. It's about giving Claude Code
          new abilities. Some let it see external tools, some let it follow fixed workflows, some let it
          farm out large tasks, and some automate repetitive actions. These abilities each have their own role.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Section 1: What are Hooks -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Hooks: Make Things Happen Automatically, Not Every Time You Remember</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Hooks are shell commands, HTTP endpoints, or LLM prompts that run automatically at specific points in
        Claude Code's lifecycle. The whole point is that "this thing will definitely happen," instead of
        leaving it up to the model to decide whether to do it.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">That makes Hooks a good fit for things like:</p>
      <ul class="usage-list">
        <li>Pop up a desktop notification every time Claude Code is waiting on you.</li>
        <li>Auto-format every file right after Claude Code edits it.</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- Main collapsible 1: Shared setup -->
      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary class="collapsible-trigger">
          <span class="collapsible-icon"></span>
          <span class="collapsible-title">One-Time Shared Setup</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="collapsible-body">
          <ol class="step-list">
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">1</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Decide where to put your hook</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Where: VS Code editor</p>
                <p class="step-desc">You can pick one of the following locations:</p>
                <ul class="inline-list">
                  <li><code>~/.claude/settings.json</code>: applies to every project.</li>
                  <li><code>.claude/settings.json</code>: applies to the current project only — good for sharing with the team.</li>
                  <li><code>.claude/settings.local.json</code>: applies to the current project only, and is usually kept out of git.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">2</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Create the file if it doesn't exist yet</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Where: VS Code file explorer + editor</p>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  If you want a project-level hook, the most common move is to create <code>.claude/settings.json</code>.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">3</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Verify with /hooks after saving</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Where: Claude Code chat box</p>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Once the settings are saved, type <code>/hooks</code> in the Claude Code chat box, then
                  pick "Hooks" followed by "Continue in Terminal."
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  You'll see which hook events were loaded successfully.
                  (If you've only followed the steps up to here, it should show <code>0 hooks configured</code>.)
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Main collapsible 2: Example 1 - desktop notification -->
      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary class="collapsible-trigger">
          <span class="collapsible-icon"></span>
          <span class="collapsible-title">Example 1: Pop a Desktop Notification When Claude Needs You</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="collapsible-body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            This hook is great for the "Claude Code is working, let me go do something else" scenario.
            The official example uses the <code>Notification</code> event, which fires whenever Claude Code
            is waiting for your input or for you to approve an action.
          </p>

          <ol class="step-list">
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">1</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Open the settings file</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Where: VS Code editor<br />
                  Open <code>.claude/settings.json</code>.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">2</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Paste in the notification hook</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Where: VS Code editor</p>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  The snippets below are straight from the official hooks guide. The <code>Notification</code>
                  event fires whenever Claude Code needs your attention; leaving <code>matcher</code> empty
                  means it runs on every occurrence of the event.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>

          <!-- Nested collapsible: Windows -->
          <details class="collapsible-nested">
            <summary class="collapsible-nested-trigger">
              <span class="collapsible-nested-icon"></span>
              <span class="collapsible-nested-title">Windows Users</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="collapsible-nested-body">
              <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`{
  "hooks": {
    "Notification": [
      {
        "matcher": "",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "powershell.exe -Command \\"[System.Reflection.Assembly]::LoadWithPartialName('System.Windows.Forms'); [System.Windows.Forms.MessageBox]::Show('Claude Code needs your attention', 'Claude Code')\\""
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}`} /></pre>
            </div>
          </details>

          <!-- Nested collapsible: Linux -->
          <details class="collapsible-nested">
            <summary class="collapsible-nested-trigger">
              <span class="collapsible-nested-icon"></span>
              <span class="collapsible-nested-title">Linux Users</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="collapsible-nested-body">
              <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`{
  "hooks": {
    "Notification": [
      {
        "matcher": "",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "notify-send 'Claude Code' 'Claude Code needs your attention'"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}`} /></pre>
            </div>
          </details>

          <!-- Nested collapsible: macOS -->
          <details class="collapsible-nested">
            <summary class="collapsible-nested-trigger">
              <span class="collapsible-nested-icon"></span>
              <span class="collapsible-nested-title">macOS Users</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="collapsible-nested-body">
              <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`{
  "hooks": {
    "Notification": [
      {
        "matcher": "",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "osascript -e 'display notification \\"Claude Code needs your attention\\" with title \\"Claude Code\\"'"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}`} /></pre>
            </div>
          </details>

          <ol class="step-list" start="3">
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">3</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Save and run a real test</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Where: Claude Code chat box</p>
                <p class="step-desc">Type:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>/hooks</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Pick "Hooks." If you see a hook listed under the <code>Notification</code> event, it's loaded.
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc">Now ask Claude Code to do something that is likely to need your approval:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>Please edit README.md and add this line at the top: This is a hooks notification test.</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Switch to another window. If everything is wired up, a notification will pop when Claude Code
                  needs you to act.
                </p>
                <figure class="figure">
                  <img
                    class="figure-img"
                    src="/learning/claude-code/通知.jpg"
                    alt="Claude Code desktop notification popup"
                    loading="lazy"
                  />
                </figure>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>

          <div class="note-card note-card--warning">
            <p class="note-body">
              <span class="note-icon" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
              <strong>Note:</strong> Running this inside VS Code will fail. The success above is based on
              running Claude Code in Windows PowerShell. Follow the steps below.
            </p>
          </div>

          <ol class="step-list sub-step-list">
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num step-num--sub">1</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Right-click your project folder and choose "Open in Terminal."</h3>
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num step-num--sub">2</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Type <code>Claude</code> and press Enter.</h3>
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num step-num--sub">3</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Right-click to paste:</h3>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>Please edit README.md and add this line at the top: This is a hooks notification test.</code></pre>
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num step-num--sub">4</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Minimize the Windows PowerShell window</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Go ahead and wait or do something else. The notification will pop at some point; when you
                  switch back to the PowerShell window, you'll see an approval prompt waiting.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>

          <div class="note-card">
            <p class="note-body">
              If Claude Code delivers notifications just fine when you run it in PowerShell but stays silent
              inside the VS Code extension, it's not on you — the VS Code extension currently has a known
              issue with the <code>Notification</code> hook. Plenty of folks have hit the same thing; it's
              an unresolved bug.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Main collapsible 3: Example 2 - auto-format -->
      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary class="collapsible-trigger">
          <span class="collapsible-icon"></span>
          <span class="collapsible-title">Example 2: Auto-Format Every File Claude Code Edits</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="collapsible-body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            This hook is great for coding. Whenever Claude Code uses Edit or Write to change a file, Prettier
            runs automatically to clean up the formatting. It uses the <code>PostToolUse</code> event paired
            with the <code>Edit|Write</code> matcher.
          </p>

          <ol class="step-list">
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">1</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Make sure Prettier is available</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Where: VS Code integrated terminal</p>
                <p class="step-desc">Install command:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>npm install --save-dev --save-exact prettier</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">Verify the install:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>npx prettier --help</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">If the help text shows up fine, the Prettier CLI is at least reachable.</p>
                <p class="step-desc">But if you see an error like the one below, PowerShell is blocking npx:</p>
                <figure class="figure">
                  <img
                    class="figure-img"
                    src="/learning/claude-code/npx error.jpg"
                    alt="PowerShell execution policy error when running npx"
                    loading="lazy"
                  />
                </figure>

                <div class="note-card note-card--warning">
                  <p class="note-body">
                    <span class="note-icon" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
                    <strong>Note:</strong> The error is likely PowerShell blocking <code>npx.ps1</code>.
                    The official PowerShell docs explain that Windows execution policy controls whether
                    scripts are allowed to run.
                  </p>
                </div>

                <p class="step-desc"><strong>Fix</strong> (Where: VS Code integrated terminal):</p>

                <div class="sub-option">
                  <h4 class="sub-option-title">Option 1: Applies to "this PowerShell window only"</h4>
                  <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope Process -ExecutionPolicy Bypass</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="sub-option">
                  <h4 class="sub-option-title">Option 2: Applies to "the current user"</h4>
                  <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope CurrentUser -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned</code></pre>
                  <p class="step-desc">
                    This affects every PowerShell window you open under this Windows account going forward,
                    but won't change settings for the whole machine (<code>CurrentUser</code> only touches
                    the current user).
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">2</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Install jq</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Where: VS Code integrated terminal</p>
                <p class="step-desc">Install command:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>winget install jqlang.jq</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">Reload the system and user PATH:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>$env:Path = [System.Environment]::GetEnvironmentVariable('Path','Machine') + ';' + [System.Environment]::GetEnvironmentVariable('Path','User')</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">Verify the install:</p>
                <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>jq --version</code></pre>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  The hook uses <code>jq</code> to parse the JSON payload Claude Code passes in, and pull
                  out the path of the file that was just edited.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">3</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Add the hook to your settings</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Where: VS Code editor</p>
                <p class="step-desc">Add this to your hooks settings:</p>
                <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`{
  "hooks": {
    "PostToolUse": [
      {
        "matcher": "Edit|Write",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "jq -r '.tool_input.file_path' | xargs npx prettier --write"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}`} /></pre>
                <p class="step-desc"><strong>What this means:</strong></p>
                <ul class="inline-list">
                  <li><code>PostToolUse</code>: fires only after a tool finishes successfully.</li>
                  <li><code>matcher: "Edit|Write"</code>: runs only when Claude edits a file.</li>
                  <li><code>jq -r '.tool_input.file_path'</code>: pulls the path of the file that was just edited.</li>
                  <li><code>xargs npx prettier --write</code>: hands that file off to Prettier for formatting.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">4</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Check after saving</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Where: Claude Code chat box</p>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Type <code>/hooks</code> and pick "Hooks" to confirm your
                  <code>PostToolUse / Edit|Write</code> entry shows up there.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">5</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Try it for real</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Where: VS Code terminal</p>

                <div class="sub-option">
                  <h4 class="sub-option-title">Step 1: Create a deliberately unformatted test file</h4>
                  <p class="step-desc">On macOS / Linux / WSL / Git Bash:</p>
                  <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`mkdir -p tmp-hook-test
cat > tmp-hook-test/hook-test.js <<'EOF'
const data={foo:"bar",items:[1,2,3]};function greet(name){console.log("Hello Hook",name,data)}
greet("world")
EOF`} /></pre>
                  <p class="step-desc">On Windows:</p>
                  <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force tmp-hook-test | Out-Null
@'
const data={foo:"bar",items:[1,2,3]};function greet(name){console.log("Hello Hook",name,data)}
greet("world")
'@ | Set-Content tmp-hook-test/hook-test.js`} /></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="sub-option">
                  <h4 class="sub-option-title">Step 2: Confirm the file is currently "unformatted"</h4>
                  <p class="step-desc">Where: VS Code terminal</p>
                  <p class="step-desc">Type:</p>
                  <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>npx prettier --check tmp-hook-test/hook-test.js</code></pre>
                  <p class="step-desc">Normally the terminal will print something like:</p>
                  <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`Checking formatting...
[warn] tmp-hook-test/hook-test.js
[warn] Code style issues found in the above file. Run Prettier with --write to fix.`} /></pre>
                  <p class="step-desc">Which means the file hasn't been formatted yet.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="sub-option">
                  <h4 class="sub-option-title">Step 3: Ask Claude for a tiny edit so the hook has a chance to fire</h4>
                  <p class="step-desc">Where: Claude Code chat box</p>
                  <p class="step-desc">Type:</p>
                  <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code set:html={`Please edit tmp-hook-test/hook-test.js:
change the string "Hello Hook" to "Hello Hook Works".
Don't add features or rewrite the content, but do clean up the formatting.`} /></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="sub-option">
                  <h4 class="sub-option-title">Step 4: Check whether the file got auto-formatted</h4>
                  <p class="step-desc">Where: VS Code terminal</p>
                  <p class="step-desc">Type:</p>
                  <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>cat tmp-hook-test/hook-test.js</code></pre>
                  <p class="step-desc">You should see it's no longer one long line — it's been reshaped into something like:</p>
                  <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`const data = { foo: "bar", items: [1, 2, 3] };
function greet(name) {
  console.log("Hello Hook Works", name, data);
}
greet("world");`} /></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="sub-option">
                  <h4 class="sub-option-title">Step 5: Run Prettier's check one more time</h4>
                  <p class="step-desc">Where: VS Code terminal</p>
                  <p class="step-desc">Type:</p>
                  <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>npx prettier --check tmp-hook-test/hook-test.js</code></pre>
                  <p class="step-desc">If the hook ran successfully, the terminal usually prints:</p>
                  <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`Checking formatting...
All matched files use Prettier code style!`} /></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Summary -->
      <div class="summary-card">
        <p class="summary-title">Key Takeaways</p>
        <ul class="summary-list">
          <li><strong>Hooks</strong>: a mechanism for running commands automatically at specific points in Claude Code's lifecycle.</li>
          <li><strong>The point is "it will definitely happen"</strong>: unlike other abilities where the model decides whether to act.</li>
          <li><strong>Settings file location</strong>: pick <code>~/.claude/settings.json</code>, a project version, or a local version depending on your need.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .cc-hooks {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Header */
  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .detail-subtitle {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  /* Section headings */
  .detail-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-paragraph {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-paragraph strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* ── Usage list ── */
  .usage-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  .usage-list li {
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
  }

  .usage-list li::before {
    content: '\2713';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .usage-list strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* ── Inline list (bulleted inside step or collapsible) ── */
  .inline-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-2) 0 var(--space-3);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-2);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .inline-list li {
    padding-left: var(--space-8);
    position: relative;
  }

  .inline-list li::before {
    content: '\2713';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  /* ── Collapsible sections (purple, top-level) ── */
  .collapsible {
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-left: 4px solid #8b5cf6;
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    overflow: hidden;
    transition: border-color var(--transition);
  }

  .collapsible[open] {
    border-top-color: #8b5cf6;
    border-right-color: #8b5cf6;
    border-bottom-color: #8b5cf6;
  }

  .collapsible-trigger {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    width: 100%;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    user-select: none;
    transition: background-color var(--transition);
  }

  .collapsible-trigger::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .collapsible-trigger:hover {
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
  }

  .collapsible-icon {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 1.25rem;
    height: 1.25rem;
    position: relative;
    transition: transform 0.2s ease;
  }

  .collapsible-icon::before,
  .collapsible-icon::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    background-color: #8b5cf6;
    border-radius: 1px;
  }

  .collapsible-icon::before {
    top: 50%;
    left: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 2px;
    transform: translateY(-50%);
